[
    {
        "content": "<p>I'd like to learn a little bit about fibre categories, at least enough to understand the \"Grothendieck construction\" and the \"category of elements\". I have the book by Jacobs <em>Categorical Logic and Type Theory</em> which looks great. </p>\n<p>Are there any other resources you would recommend for learning about fibre categories?</p>",
        "id": 268899606,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1642797301
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is an unusual answer, but the first source I learned about it from is <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1411.3038\">Christina Vasilakopoulou's thesis</a>.</p>",
        "id": 268901500,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1642798301
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Weird synchronicity -- I feel like this is the third or fourth time I've heard this question in the past week or two.  Two references that I've given are volume 2 chapter 8 of <em>Handbook of categorical algebra</em>, and chapter B1 of <em>Sketches of an Elephant</em>, .  But I don't really feel like I have a good answer to this question; there are a number of modern \"introduction to category theory\" textbooks, but do any of them reach the Grothendieck construction?</p>",
        "id": 268902211,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1642798710
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think <a href=\"https://math.jhu.edu/~eriehl/context/\">Riehl</a> talks about the category of elements.</p>",
        "id": 268902294,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1642798781
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2002.06055\">Johnson and Yau</a> dedicate two chapters to it I think.</p>",
        "id": 268902503,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1642798843
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Something to keep in mind <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277503\">@David Egolf</span>  is that you either talk at the level of presheaves and the category of elements, or you must talk about 2-categorical things. This will skew what sources will talk about it.</p>",
        "id": 268903213,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1642799163
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Jacobs' book is definitely a good source on the grothendieck construction, it's fundamental for him</p>",
        "id": 268904900,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1642800112
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks everyone, those look great!</p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275914\">Joe Moeller</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/learning.20about.20fibre.20categories/near/268903213\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Something to keep in mind <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277503\">David Egolf</span>  is that you either talk at the level of presheaves and the category of elements, or you must talk about 2-categorical things. This will skew what sources will talk about it.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That is good to know. 2-categorical things still scare me, so that will limit which sources I work from.</p>",
        "id": 268905052,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1642800201
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Johnson and Yau is a good reference, thanks for pointing that out Joe.  Reading their earlier chapters might be a good way to get over a fear of 2-categories.  (-:</p>",
        "id": 268913716,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1642805188
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Chapter 12 in <a href=\"http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/reprints/articles/22/tr22abs.html\">Barr and Wells - Category Theory for Computing Science</a> covers Fibrations and the Grothendieck construction. It is where I first learnt about it.</p>",
        "id": 268914341,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1642805576
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It is a fairly gentle introduction which from memory does not use 2-categories</p>",
        "id": 268914412,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1642805640
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What is your background?</p>",
        "id": 268914760,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1642805874
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think we're talking about \"fibred categories\", not \"fibre categories\", right?</p>",
        "id": 268919198,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642808653
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/learning.20about.20fibred.20categories/near/268919198\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think we're talking about \"fibred categories\", not \"fibre categories\", right?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes. I've updated the title.</p>",
        "id": 268921046,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1642809974
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275989\">Paolo Perrone</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/learning.20about.20fibred.20categories/near/268914760\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>What is your background?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I have an engineering background. I've self-taught myself some basics of category theory working from <em>Seven Sketches</em> and RIehl's <em>Category Theory in Context</em> (as well as few other math things like introductory real analysis, introductory abstract algebra, and introductory topology).</p>\n<p>John Baez told me that a category I'm interested in for thinking about observations in the context of imaging (see <a class=\"stream-topic\" data-stream-id=\"229156\" href=\"/#narrow/stream/229156-practice.3A-applied-ct/topic/spans.20and.20images\">#practice: applied ct &gt; spans and images</a>) is the \"category of elements of a presheaf category\". That's one reason I'd like to learn what a\"category of elements\" is.</p>\n<p>So, a lot of these resources will be a bit hard for me. But some of them look approachable!</p>",
        "id": 268921874,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1642810555
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'll just tell you: given a functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><msup><mi>C</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F: C^{\\mathrm{ op}} \\to \\mathsf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, an <strong>element</strong> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> is an element of some set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F(c)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, and a <strong>morphism</strong> from the element <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\in F(c)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> to the element <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo>∈</mo><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mi>c</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x&#x27; \\in F(c&#x27;)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.791em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0019em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is a morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><msup><mi>c</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f : c&#x27; \\to c</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span></span></span></span> such that </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F(f)(x) = x&#x27;</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>Elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> and the morphisms between them form the <strong>category of elements</strong> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 268926230,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642814188
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can see that you've got a special case of this in your comment <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229156-practice.3A-applied.20ct/topic/spans.20and.20images/near/268884777\">here</a>. </p>\n<p>If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Open}(Y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Open</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is the poset of open subsets of your topological space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> there's a functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>Y</mi><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mtext>op</mtext></msup><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F: \\mathrm{Open}(Y)^{\\textrm{op}} \\to \\mathrm{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Open</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord textrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>U</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F(U)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is the set of functions <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>U</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f: U \\to H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span>.   I'll let you guess what this functor does on morphisms - it does the only imaginable thing.</p>",
        "id": 268926501,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642814437
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can check that the category you cooked up from this situation is the category of elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 268926596,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642814528
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for explaining that!<br>\nI'm taking a little break from this today, but I'll give this some proper consideration later this weekend.</p>",
        "id": 268926679,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1642814633
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F: \\mathrm{C}^{\\mathrm{op}} \\to \\mathrm{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> is called a <strong>presheaf</strong>, and your example is one of the basic examples that made people invent presheaves.   An even more typical example would be if you let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>U</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F(U)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> consist of <em>continuous</em> functions  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>U</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f: U \\to H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span>, assuming <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span> has some topology.   Then you'd actually be <em>using</em> the topology on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> in a real way.</p>",
        "id": 268926792,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642814715
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi all, I have been working on some (slightly idiosyncratic) lecture notes on the topic of fibered category theory. I caution you because it is very provisional and I have not yet given much motivation or examples, as I am first trying to work out the theory in a way that I like. <a href=\"http://www.jonmsterling.com/math/lectures/categorical-foundations.html\">http://www.jonmsterling.com/math/lectures/categorical-foundations.html</a></p>",
        "id": 268948931,
        "sender_full_name": "Jon Sterling",
        "timestamp": 1642844882
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another good set of notes is <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1801.02927\">these by Streicher</a></p>",
        "id": 268949254,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1642845369
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I really like Thomas's notes too. They are a very important source for me.</p>",
        "id": 268950704,
        "sender_full_name": "Jon Sterling",
        "timestamp": 1642847618
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the first step though is to internalise the Grothendieck construction at the level of presheaves of sets. </p>\n<p>If you’re interested in algebraic/differential geometry, then you can try and translate many geometric constructions on schemes/manifolds to their categories of (affine) elements.</p>",
        "id": 268951425,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1642848725
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's a good idea; I am not a geometer, but from what little I know of scheme theory the category of elements is very natural for  geometry because one is considering at all times not just global points, but generalized points. The category of elements makes this explicit.</p>",
        "id": 268952915,
        "sender_full_name": "Jon Sterling",
        "timestamp": 1642850827
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks again, everyone.</p>",
        "id": 269025916,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1642954617
    }
]